# =============================================================================
# DXA Agent Environment Configuration
# =============================================================================
#
# Who this file is for
# --------------------
#   - **New to AI (but comfortable with files / terminals):** read
#     "If you are new to AI services" below, then follow "HOW TO USE".
#   - **Developers:** dotenv-style `KEY=value` → process env; same names as
#     shell exports. Jump to PROVIDER SELECTION; see SYSTEM-WIDE SETUP and
#     docs/advanced-setup.md for CI, Bun, and build workflows.
#   - **New to coding or first time using `.env`:** use the repo docs instead
#     of learning that here — docs/non-technical-setup.md,
#     docs/quick-start-windows.md, docs/quick-start-mac-linux.md,
#     docs/setup-checklist.md.
#
# If you are new to AI services (plain English)
# ----------------------------------------------
#   DXA Agent is the app you run; it still needs an **AI backend** to generate
#   answers. That is either:
#     - **Cloud:** a vendor (Anthropic, OpenAI, Google, GitHub, …) gives you an
#       **API key** (a secret string from their console). Put it in `.env` or
#       in your system environment. Never commit keys or paste them in public
#       chats or screenshots.
#     - **Local:** **Ollama** or **LM Studio** runs a **model** on your machine
#       (no vendor key, or a dummy key). Install the app, download a model,
#       start the server, then use Option 5 or 6 below.
#   **Provider** = which API or local tool you use. **Model** = which model
#   name to request (vendor docs or the name shown in Ollama / LM Studio).
#   Optional lines below override default model or base URL.
#
# For developers
# ------------
#   Standard `.env` / dotenv semantics. Values override shell env depending on
#   loader; system-wide copy-paste patterns are in SYSTEM-WIDE SETUP below.
#
# HOW TO USE THIS FILE
# --------------------
#   1) Copy to `.env`:  cp .env.example .env  (Windows: Copy-Item or copy)
#   2) Uncomment **one** provider block under PROVIDER SELECTION (remove leading
#      `#` only on that block's lines).
#   3) Replace placeholders with your real key, token, model id, or URLs.
#
# Only set variables for the provider you use. All other sections stay commented.
#
# Later sections: "OPTIONAL TUNING" tweaks behaviour. "SYSTEM-WIDE SETUP" explains
# how to set the same variables globally (any folder) instead of using .env,
# with copy-paste examples per OS. You can skip that until you need it.
#
# =============================================================================

# =============================================================================
# PROVIDER SELECTION — uncomment ONE block below
# =============================================================================
#
# Which block is mine? (open only the matching section under this line)
# -------------------------------------------------------------------------
#   1  Anthropic / Claude — API key from https://console.anthropic.com/
#   2  OpenAI or OpenAI-compatible cloud (key from provider's dashboard)
#   3  Google Gemini (key from Google AI Studio / Cloud)
#   4  GitHub Models (personal access token with models access)
#   5  Ollama — free local app; download models inside Ollama first
#   6  LM Studio — local app; enable "Developer" server and load a model
#   7  AWS Bedrock — corporate / AWS account; often needs `aws configure` too
#   8  Google Vertex AI — GCP project; enterprise-style Google Cloud setup
# -------------------------------------------------------------------------

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Option 1: Anthropic (default — no provider flag needed)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-your-key-here

# Override the default model (optional)
# ANTHROPIC_MODEL=claude-sonnet-4-5

# Use a custom Anthropic-compatible endpoint (optional)
# ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL=https://api.anthropic.com


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Option 2: OpenAI
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CLAUDE_CODE_USE_OPENAI=1
# OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-your-key-here
# OPENAI_MODEL=gpt-4o

# Use a custom OpenAI-compatible endpoint (optional — defaults to api.openai.com)
# OPENAI_BASE_URL=https://api.openai.com/v1


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Option 3: Google Gemini
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CLAUDE_CODE_USE_GEMINI=1
# GEMINI_API_KEY=your-gemini-key-here
# GEMINI_MODEL=gemini-2.0-flash

# Use a custom Gemini endpoint (optional)
# GEMINI_BASE_URL=https://generativelanguage.googleapis.com/v1beta/openai


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Option 4: GitHub Models
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CLAUDE_CODE_USE_GITHUB=1
# GITHUB_TOKEN=ghp_your-token-here


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Option 5: Ollama (local models)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CLAUDE_CODE_USE_OPENAI=1
# OPENAI_BASE_URL=http://localhost:11434/v1
# OPENAI_API_KEY=ollama
# OPENAI_MODEL=llama3.2

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Option 6: LM Studio (local models)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# LM Studio exposes an OpenAI-compatible API, so we use the OpenAI provider.
# Make sure LM Studio is running with the Developer server enabled
# (Developer tab > toggle server ON).
#
# Steps:
#   1. Download and install LM Studio from https://lmstudio.ai
#   2. Search for and download a model (e.g. any coding or instruct model)
#   3. Load the model and start the Developer server
#   4. Set OPENAI_MODEL to the model ID shown in LM Studio's Developer tab
#
# The default server URL is http://localhost:1234 — change the port below
# if you've configured a different one in LM Studio.
#
# OPENAI_API_KEY is optional — LM Studio runs locally and ignores it.
# Some clients require a non-empty value; if you get auth errors, set it
# to any dummy value (e.g. "lmstudio").
#
# CLAUDE_CODE_USE_OPENAI=1
# OPENAI_BASE_URL=http://localhost:1234/v1
# OPENAI_MODEL=your-model-id-here


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Option 7: AWS Bedrock
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# You may also need AWS CLI credentials configured (run: aws configure)
# or have AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID and AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY set in your
# environment in addition to the variables below.
#
# CLAUDE_CODE_USE_BEDROCK=1
# AWS_REGION=us-east-1
# AWS_DEFAULT_REGION=us-east-1
# AWS_BEARER_TOKEN_BEDROCK=your-bearer-token-here
# ANTHROPIC_BEDROCK_BASE_URL=https://bedrock-runtime.us-east-1.amazonaws.com


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Option 8: Google Vertex AI
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CLAUDE_CODE_USE_VERTEX=1
# ANTHROPIC_VERTEX_PROJECT_ID=your-gcp-project-id
# CLOUD_ML_REGION=us-east5
# GOOGLE_CLOUD_PROJECT=your-gcp-project-id


# =============================================================================
# OPTIONAL — Python helpers (python/ folder)
# =============================================================================
#
# The main DXA Agent CLI (Bun / TypeScript) uses PROVIDER SELECTION above
# (ANTHROPIC_*, CLAUDE_CODE_USE_*, OPENAI_*, etc.). The variables below are
# only for OPTIONAL scripts under python/ — Ollama / Atomic Chat helpers and the
# experimental smart_router sketch. Skip this block unless you run that code.
#
# pip install -r python/requirements.txt
#
# --- Local URLs (defaults shown) ---------------------------------------------
# OLLAMA_BASE_URL=http://localhost:11434
# ATOMIC_CHAT_BASE_URL=http://127.0.0.1:1337
#
# --- Model hints for smart_router.build_default_providers() -----------------
# BIG_MODEL=gpt-4.1
# SMALL_MODEL=gpt-4.1-mini
#
# --- Smart router (python/smart_router.py only) ------------------------------
# ROUTER_STRATEGY=balanced    # latency | cost | balanced
# ROUTER_FALLBACK=true
#
# Cloud keys for the Python router catalogue (if you use smart_router):
# OPENAI_API_KEY=...
# GEMINI_API_KEY=...


# =============================================================================
# OPTIONAL TUNING
# =============================================================================
#
# Skip this whole section unless you have a specific need (retries, timeouts,
# debug logs, terminal key quirks). Defaults work for most people.
#
# Max number of API retries on failure (default: 10)
# CLAUDE_CODE_MAX_RETRIES=10

# Enable persistent retry mode for unattended/CI sessions
# Retries 429/529 indefinitely with smart backoff
# CLAUDE_CODE_UNATTENDED_RETRY=1

# Enable extended key reporting (Kitty keyboard protocol)
# Useful for iTerm2, WezTerm, Ghostty if modifier keys feel off
# DXA_AGENT_ENABLE_EXTENDED_KEYS=1

# Disable "Co-authored-by" line in git commits made by DXA Agent
# DXA_AGENT_DISABLE_CO_AUTHORED_BY=1

# Custom timeout for API requests in milliseconds (default: varies)
# API_TIMEOUT_MS=60000

# Enable debug logging
# CLAUDE_DEBUG=1


# =============================================================================
# SYSTEM-WIDE SETUP (OPTIONAL)
# =============================================================================
#
# Use this section if you prefer not to use a `.env` file in one folder — for
# example you want DXA Agent to work from any directory after opening a
# terminal. Same variable names as above; the lists below are a quick
# reference plus copy-paste steps for Mac, Linux, and Windows.
#
# Instead of using a .env file per project, you can set these variables
# system-wide so DXA Agent works from any directory on your machine.
#
# STEP 1: Pick your provider variables from the list below.
# STEP 2: Set them using the method for your OS (see further down).
#
# --- Provider variables (same names as above; quick reference) ---------------
#
#   Option 1 — Anthropic:
#     ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-your-key-here
#     ANTHROPIC_MODEL=claude-sonnet-4-5              (optional)
#     ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL=https://api.anthropic.com   (optional)
#
#   Option 2 — OpenAI:
#     CLAUDE_CODE_USE_OPENAI=1
#     OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-your-key-here
#     OPENAI_MODEL=gpt-4o
#     OPENAI_BASE_URL=https://api.openai.com/v1      (optional)
#
#   Option 3 — Google Gemini:
#     CLAUDE_CODE_USE_GEMINI=1
#     GEMINI_API_KEY=your-gemini-key-here
#     GEMINI_MODEL=gemini-2.0-flash
#     GEMINI_BASE_URL=https://generativelanguage.googleapis.com  (optional)
#
#   Option 4 — GitHub Models:
#     CLAUDE_CODE_USE_GITHUB=1
#     GITHUB_TOKEN=ghp_your-token-here
#
#   Option 5 — Ollama (local):
#     CLAUDE_CODE_USE_OPENAI=1
#     OPENAI_BASE_URL=http://localhost:11434/v1
#     OPENAI_API_KEY=ollama
#     OPENAI_MODEL=llama3.2
#
#   Option 6 — LM Studio (local):
#     CLAUDE_CODE_USE_OPENAI=1
#     OPENAI_BASE_URL=http://localhost:1234/v1
#     OPENAI_MODEL=your-model-id-here
#     OPENAI_API_KEY=lmstudio                        (optional)
#
#   Option 7 — AWS Bedrock (may also need: aws configure):
#     CLAUDE_CODE_USE_BEDROCK=1
#     AWS_REGION=us-east-1
#     AWS_DEFAULT_REGION=us-east-1
#     AWS_BEARER_TOKEN_BEDROCK=your-bearer-token-here
#     ANTHROPIC_BEDROCK_BASE_URL=https://bedrock-runtime.us-east-1.amazonaws.com
#
#   Option 8 — Google Vertex AI:
#     CLAUDE_CODE_USE_VERTEX=1
#     ANTHROPIC_VERTEX_PROJECT_ID=your-gcp-project-id
#     CLOUD_ML_REGION=us-east5
#     GOOGLE_CLOUD_PROJECT=your-gcp-project-id
#
# --- How to set variables on each OS ----------------------------------------
#
# macOS (zsh):
#   1. Open:  nano ~/.zshrc
#   2. Add each variable as:  export VAR_NAME=value
#   3. Save and reload:  source ~/.zshrc
#
# Linux (bash):
#   1. Open:  nano ~/.bashrc
#   2. Add each variable as:  export VAR_NAME=value
#   3. Save and reload:  source ~/.bashrc
#
# Windows (PowerShell):
#   Run for each variable:
#     [System.Environment]::SetEnvironmentVariable('VAR_NAME', 'value', 'User')
#   Then restart your terminal.
#
# Windows (Command Prompt):
#   Run for each variable:
#     setx VAR_NAME value
#   Then restart your terminal.
#
# Windows (GUI):
#   Settings > System > About > Advanced System Settings >
#   Environment Variables > under "User variables" click New,
#   then add each variable.
#
# --- Important notes --------------------------------------------------------
#
# LOCAL SERVERS: If using LM Studio or Ollama, the server MUST be
# running with a model loaded before you launch DXA Agent —
# otherwise you'll get connection errors.
#
# SWITCHING PROVIDERS: To temporarily switch, unset the relevant
# variables in your current terminal session:
#
#   macOS / Linux:
#     unset VAR_NAME
#     # e.g.: unset CLAUDE_CODE_USE_OPENAI OPENAI_BASE_URL OPENAI_MODEL
#
#   Windows (PowerShell — current session only):
#     Remove-Item Env:VAR_NAME
#
#   To permanently remove a variable on Windows:
#     [System.Environment]::SetEnvironmentVariable('VAR_NAME', $null, 'User')
#
# LOAD ORDER:
#   Shell and system environment variables are inherited by the process.
#   Project .env files are only used if your launcher or shell loads them
#   before starting DXA Agent.
# COMPATIBILITY:
#   System-wide variables work regardless of how you run DXA Agent:
#   npx, global npm install, bun run, or node directly. Any process
#   launched from your terminal inherits your shell's environment.
#
# REMINDER: Make sure .env is in your .gitignore to avoid committing secrets.
# =============================================================================
